pullRequest.title: [#9651] Enhance Jmeter result population upon running test
pullRequest.bodyText:
Fixes #9651
This PR is a continuation of the now defunct PR, that stagnated due to the original contributor leaving.
Content below are all copied from the previous PR. Work done credit to @jacoblipech.
Current approach:
Generate a statistics file using the ReportGenerator. A statistics.json file will be generated used to showcase the results in 4 key areas.
The bulk of the files are Jmeter.configuration file to ensure that ReportGenerator works since it Teammates no longer require to download Jmeter to run the tests.
The output looks something like this:

Tried approach:


Makes use of the Calculator class in Jmeter to automatically calculate these metrics. However, the Calculator class requires that each SampleResult object to be added in order to calculate, hence creating a new MyResultCollector class to overwrite ResultCollector.


Read each line from .jml file and do manual calculation of each end point to calculate throughput. Need additional space and not as accurate as the Calculator class. Can consider overwriting existing Calculator class to make use of the methods provided.


Summariser used in logging the Jmeter tests does not contain useful information and cannot be used to determine the throughput error rate etc as it only accounts for the total number of tests cases ran, not breakdown of individual end points.


 Shows throughput, 90 percentile line of latency, error rate and average latency of each test end point


 Find baseline comparison to comment on the result found (currently only error rate & mean response time)


 Ability to change configuration file using a java class (on-hold)


 Ensure log is shown on travis as well (done in #9671)


 Remove unnecessary dependency files

nodes.bodyText: Will this cause race condition if multiple LNP is run concurrently?
I think a better approach is to create a LNPSpecificiation somewhat class to hold the limit and put into the super class of the LNPTest.
Continue from my point, by SRP principle, Statistics should not be responsible to check limit.
